cool games, but at the end of the day, they are also just humans.

222
00:15:11,317 --> 00:15:15,742
And trying not to be too starstruck was one of the best advices that I've ever gotten.

223
00:15:16,403 --> 00:15:19,326
And they presumably like games just as much as you do.

224
00:15:19,446 --> 00:15:22,469
And if they do not want to talk to you, they will let you know.

225
00:15:24,626 --> 00:15:28,907
But please do not miss out on a chance to talk to someone that you're truly inspired

226
00:15:28,967 --> 00:15:33,929
by because you think you're not good enough or you have nothing of value to contribute

227
00:15:34,229 --> 00:15:35,349
to that conversation.

228
00:15:36,349 --> 00:15:41,331
So I'd say use some well-deserved confidence, please not too much, and build up your own

229
00:15:41,351 --> 00:15:44,151
network and I'm very sure that you can do it.

230
00:15:45,257 --> 00:15:47,518
So if you then found someone you want to work with,

231
00:15:48,238 --> 00:15:49,579
then you might need a portfolio,

232
00:15:50,019 --> 00:15:52,380
and that will be brought to you by Raymond in the next piece.

233
00:15:52,820 --> 00:15:54,181
So thank you for listening.

234
00:15:54,481 --> 00:15:55,941
Make sure to ask all the questions,

235
00:15:56,021 --> 00:15:57,442
and if you still have more questions,

236
00:15:57,522 --> 00:15:58,562
reach out to me on Twitter.

237
00:15:59,463 --> 00:16:01,384
Thanks again, and say hi to Raymond.

238
00:16:02,324 --> 00:16:02,964
Hello, everybody.

239
00:16:03,104 --> 00:16:03,644
My name is Raymond.

240
00:16:03,885 --> 00:16:04,645
I'm a level designer,

241
00:16:04,805 --> 00:16:06,726
and I have my own indie studio called RoofCant.

242
00:16:07,146 --> 00:16:08,526
Thank you so much for coming to our talk.

243
00:16:09,611 --> 00:16:13,572
I should just introduce you to getting your own network and getting started.

244
00:16:13,852 --> 00:16:17,053
Once you've actually got your network, it's going to be really important to be able to

245
00:16:17,093 --> 00:16:18,474
show people what exactly you can do.

246
00:16:18,874 --> 00:16:20,974
And that's where portfolios come in extremely handy.

247
00:16:21,254 --> 00:16:25,816
So I'm going to give you a number of practical tips on how to get the most out of your portfolio.

248
00:16:26,891 --> 00:16:29,292
Starting off, finishing a game is incredibly difficult.

249
00:16:29,452 --> 00:16:32,453
So if you actually manage to get through the entire game development process,

250
00:16:32,813 --> 00:16:35,654
maybe even release your game on something like itch.io or on Steam,

251
00:16:35,954 --> 00:16:37,494
that's fantastic to show on your portfolio.

252
00:16:37,974 --> 00:16:41,636
It shows that you've actually gone through all of the different phases in game development

253
00:16:41,936 --> 00:16:45,297
and got the experience out of that, on top of being extremely perseverant

254
00:16:45,537 --> 00:16:47,457
for being able to actually complete an entire game.

255
00:16:47,938 --> 00:16:50,558
That's something that not a lot of people just entering the industry have,

256
00:16:50,618 --> 00:16:52,419
so that's fantastic to show on your portfolio.

257
00:16:53,827 --> 00:16:57,448
Secondly, it's going to be really important to show that you can collaborate in a team and work

258
00:16:57,488 --> 00:17:01,130
together with others because very likely that's what you're going to be doing at whatever company

259
00:17:01,250 --> 00:17:04,971
you're applying for. So if you've got any school projects that you've done together with other

260
00:17:04,991 --> 00:17:08,453
students, if you've done any game jams together in a team, that's fantastic to show in your

261
00:17:08,473 --> 00:17:12,655
portfolio as well. Now if you don't have any of this experience working in a team, as has been

262
00:17:12,695 --> 00:17:16,496
mentioned before in this talk, game jams are a fantastic opportunity to get started.

263
00:17:17,857 --> 00:17:21,398
One thing that is really important when you are showing off work that you've done in a team

264
00:17:21,758 --> 00:17:26,379
is to explain what exactly you did. Show what your contribution was. For example,

265
00:17:26,459 --> 00:17:29,860
if you're an environment artist and you're showing a screenshot of the project you did

266
00:17:29,920 --> 00:17:33,862
and they chose a really beautiful looking building and then some random floating cubes right next to

267
00:17:33,922 --> 00:17:38,483
it, people might judge you on the entire thing if you don't explain that you made that beautiful

268
00:17:38,523 --> 00:17:42,384
looking building and some level designer decided it would be fun to place cubes everywhere because

269
00:17:42,404 --> 00:17:43,825
that's what we level designers love to do.

270
00:17:44,837 --> 00:17:49,364
So basically make it very clear what exactly you did on the project and that becomes even more

271
00:17:49,424 --> 00:17:53,291
important when you've worked together with other people of the same discipline. If you work together

272
00:17:53,331 --> 00:17:57,498
with three other environment artists it's even more relevant to show what is yours and what is

273
00:17:57,518 --> 00:17:58,519
the work of somebody else.

274
00:18:00,142 --> 00:18:04,543
Now if your work is a lot less visual, for example you're a game designer, you're a programmer, maybe you're a producer,

275
00:18:05,043 --> 00:18:10,245
it can be really helpful to illustrate your process to show what kind of things you thought about,

276
00:18:10,345 --> 00:18:13,705
what kind of decisions you made throughout the process of creating this project.

277
00:18:14,286 --> 00:18:19,427
This can really give the person who is reviewing your portfolio an idea of whether you have the

278
00:18:19,447 --> 00:18:23,328
kind of game development insight or the kind of problem-solving skills that they are looking for.

279
00:18:24,493 --> 00:18:27,735
that's also really relevant to show work that you've done in your personal time.

280
00:18:28,235 --> 00:18:32,658
Things that you have spent your free, personal, precious time on can really show what motivates

281
00:18:32,678 --> 00:18:37,381
you and especially if that fits with whatever you're applying for, that can be really helpful

282
00:18:37,621 --> 00:18:41,624
to show that you're passionate about this thing you actually are gonna hopefully be doing for money.

283
00:18:43,365 --> 00:18:46,528
Now, all right, I've just shown you a number of things that would be really good to include in

284
00:18:46,548 --> 00:18:51,773
your portfolio, but obviously pick your best stuff. You shouldn't show a whole list of 20

285
00:18:52,273 --> 00:18:55,796
projects that you did out of which some are really good and some are kind of mediocre,

286
00:18:56,136 --> 00:18:59,940
because the person looking at your portfolio is not going to have a lot of time. And so if they

287
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:03,583
scroll through your portfolio and click on one that happens to not be your best project,

288
00:19:03,943 --> 00:19:06,265
then they're going to judge you based on that. And that would be a shame.

289
00:19:06,806 --> 00:19:10,308
I've actually done this quite wrong myself at some point when I had an interview and

290
00:19:10,328 --> 00:19:14,249
I was asked to walk through my portfolio, kind of show the different types of experiences

291
00:19:14,790 --> 00:19:15,170
I've had.

292
00:19:15,610 --> 00:19:19,912
And I started with a game jam that I did, which, you know, I liked, but it wasn't my

293
00:19:19,952 --> 00:19:24,634
best work because I thought I would build it up to this awesome stuff I really wanted

294
00:19:24,654 --> 00:19:25,134
to talk about.

295
00:19:25,194 --> 00:19:28,436
And then they started asking me critical questions about this game jam that I did.

296
00:19:28,456 --> 00:19:32,157
And I just was like, please, can we move on to the stuff I'm more proud of?

297
00:19:32,978 --> 00:19:33,698
That was a bad idea.

298
00:19:33,818 --> 00:19:34,638
Please do not do that.

299
00:19:36,299 --> 00:19:40,462
So you want to show your best stuff, but you also want to make sure that you really take into account

300
00:19:40,502 --> 00:19:44,385
what exactly you're applying for. If you're applying for AAA, then the people looking at

301
00:19:44,425 --> 00:19:48,887
your portfolio are going to expect a much more specialized skill set. If you're looking for

302
00:19:48,908 --> 00:19:53,330
an indie project, if you're joining an indie team, then they might actually be quite happy

303
00:19:53,350 --> 00:19:54,791
that you can do multiple different things.

304
00:19:55,888 --> 00:20:03,975
What's also really interesting is to consider whether any of the products you've done fit directly into the kind of work that the company you're applying for does.

305
00:20:04,055 --> 00:20:15,665
For example, if you're an artist and you've made work in the style that the company you're applying for uses, that can be really relevant because that lets them see immediately whether you would be a good fit for their team and their kind of projects.

306
00:20:16,145 --> 00:20:24,312
With game designers or programmers, that would be something like working on systems that these companies that you're applying for have used in the past.

307
00:20:26,182 --> 00:20:30,225
Lastly, very important, get feedback. Show others your portfolio, show it to your friends,

308
00:20:30,625 --> 00:20:35,528
to other people that are looking for a job in the industry. Try and get portfolio reviews because

309
00:20:35,949 --> 00:20:39,711
just like a game, your portfolio is never finished. You can keep improving on it and

310
00:20:40,212 --> 00:20:43,194
hopefully at some point you won't need to anymore because you will have a job. Yay!

311
00:20:44,245 --> 00:20:45,386
All right, that was my list.

312
00:20:46,427 --> 00:20:51,451
And now that I have a little bit of time left, I can actually go through one example of my

313
00:20:51,651 --> 00:20:52,231
own portfolio.

314
00:20:52,692 --> 00:20:54,533
So this is a project I did in university.

315
00:20:54,593 --> 00:20:57,856
If you go to the front page of my portfolio, scroll through it a bit, you'll find this.

316
00:20:58,516 --> 00:21:01,959
And what this already shows you is it shows a little bit about what the actual game is,

317
00:21:01,979 --> 00:21:05,582
but it also shows some awards recognition, why you might care, why you might want to

318
00:21:05,602 --> 00:21:05,942
click on this.

319
00:21:06,502 --> 00:21:10,766
and it immediately shows some of that my contribution part that I was talking about earlier

320
00:21:11,347 --> 00:21:16,372
because this was a team of 18 people, more at some point, so I think it's really important

321
00:21:16,392 --> 00:21:19,115
to immediately highlight this is the part that I actually worked on.

322
00:21:20,253 --> 00:21:24,276
Now, if you click on the project page, you're going to see a lot of just kind of standard info.

323
00:21:24,296 --> 00:21:26,338
You see the trailer, you see a description fact sheet.

324
00:21:26,758 --> 00:21:30,381
But if you then go further, you will see my contribution worked out much more.

325
00:21:30,401 --> 00:21:38,407
I show illustrations that I made to kind of highlight how I try to communicate to the rest of the team what I thought this game might look like at some point.

326
00:21:38,727 --> 00:21:44,891
You see prototypes that I made where I tested out whether the mechanics we were trying to work with, whether they would actually work, whether they would be fun.

327
00:21:45,512 --> 00:21:50,814
We actually tried out a bunch of puzzles in that, and I explained that in these few images.

328
00:21:51,454 --> 00:21:53,875
It shows some of the sketches, some of the illustrations that I made.

329
00:21:54,415 --> 00:21:58,837
And showing all of this, obviously, not everybody going through my portfolio is going to read all of this.

330
00:21:59,257 --> 00:22:03,379
But seeing all these different methods that I used, hopefully will give them an idea of my process,

331
00:22:03,479 --> 00:22:06,260
of how I work, and whether I would be a good fit in their team.

332
00:22:07,813 --> 00:22:09,155
So that was my part of this talk.

333
00:22:09,195 --> 00:22:10,195
Thank you so much for listening.

334
00:22:10,456 --> 00:22:11,256
If you want to stay in touch,

335
00:22:11,276 --> 00:22:13,658
you can reach me on Twitter at Roof Guide Games.

336
00:22:14,579 --> 00:22:16,340
And up next, Diana will give you some insight

337
00:22:16,380 --> 00:22:18,362
from her perspective as a recruiter.

338
00:22:18,802 --> 00:22:19,583
Thank you so much for listening.

339
00:22:19,963 --> 00:22:20,603
See you in the industry.

340
00:22:21,024 --> 00:22:22,625
Hi everyone, I'm Diana,

341
00:22:22,945 --> 00:22:25,788
and I welcome you to my talk, Inside Recruiting.

342
00:22:27,109 --> 00:22:29,831
I've been working in the industry for about 80 years now

343
00:22:29,991 --> 00:22:33,674
in varying capacities, one of which is as a recruiter.

344
00:22:33,994 --> 00:22:37,216
And as such, I've seen very different kinds of applications.

345
00:22:38,158 --> 00:22:41,399
Now that Raymond told you about how to set up a great portfolio,

346
00:22:41,799 --> 00:22:44,460
I would like to tell you how we might look at your application.

347
00:22:45,120 --> 00:22:48,962
What else we'd like to know about you, and especially how not to apply.

348
00:22:49,782 --> 00:22:53,023
So the first thing I will usually see is your

349
00:22:53,183 --> 00:22:58,385
email address or username. Please get a proper email address.

350
00:22:59,245 --> 00:23:03,967
Usually the chances for son of a bitch or mafia militia are not very high to be

351
00:23:03,987 --> 00:23:04,887
taken seriously.

352
00:23:05,864 --> 00:23:08,386
And also, if you maybe have multiple email addresses,

353
00:23:09,086 --> 00:23:11,048
check if you are locked into the proper one

354
00:23:11,088 --> 00:23:12,909
before sending out your application.

355
00:23:13,610 --> 00:23:14,911
You might regret it otherwise.

356
00:23:16,192 --> 00:23:17,613
The same thing goes for username.

357
00:23:18,334 --> 00:23:21,736
If you contact me on Discord or another platform, which

358
00:23:21,877 --> 00:23:24,699
actually might happen if I'm looking

359
00:23:24,779 --> 00:23:28,222
for a small indie company, and then you

360
00:23:28,262 --> 00:23:30,804
don't have your real name as a username,

361
00:23:31,244 --> 00:23:35,428
please start the actual chat with, hi, my name is.

362
00:23:37,174 --> 00:23:43,079
A name only consisting of maybe emojis and no follow up to get to know who you actually

363
00:23:43,279 --> 00:23:48,223
are is not what I would like to see on a first base for a job interview.

364
00:23:49,544 --> 00:23:52,426
The next important thing is please talk to me.

365
00:23:52,446 --> 00:24:00,633
Hi is not really an application and please get me this job isn't either.

366
00:24:01,754 --> 00:24:06,217
This is really not a good way to address your recruiter and to introduce yourself to them.

367
00:24:07,173 --> 00:24:10,455
The same goes for almost empty messages or emails.

368
00:24:11,075 --> 00:24:13,136
We are usually asking for certain documents,

369
00:24:13,236 --> 00:24:16,337
and I cannot count the times I receive an application

370
00:24:16,918 --> 00:24:18,118
with almost nothing in there.

371
00:24:19,299 --> 00:24:22,120
So please, say something about who you are,

372
00:24:22,540 --> 00:24:24,681
what you've worked on before, and please

373
00:24:24,741 --> 00:24:26,542
attach the documents and information

374
00:24:26,602 --> 00:24:27,522
we are asking for.

375
00:24:27,642 --> 00:24:28,562
We sure want them.

376
00:24:29,963 --> 00:24:31,584
But how do you start it all?

377
00:24:32,924 --> 00:24:35,145
First off, read the job posting.

378
00:24:36,069 --> 00:24:41,492
Show me that you actually understood what I am looking for and that this is why you are writing to me.

379
00:24:42,212 --> 00:24:46,815
Also, never offer your talent for free, especially not if I'm offering a paid role.

380
00:24:47,835 --> 00:24:51,077
Make sure that you specify what you are applying for.

381
00:24:51,477 --> 00:24:56,600
I might actually have several openings, even for different companies, if we talk indie freelance.

382
00:24:57,440 --> 00:25:03,144
So mention which company and which position you are applying for and introduce yourself with your profession.

383
00:25:07,238 --> 00:25:11,420
On the other hand, of course, you can always send in an unsolicited application.

384
00:25:11,940 --> 00:25:14,642
Maybe you are lucky and we are actually looking for you.

385
00:25:15,242 --> 00:25:17,744
Some companies even offer that option on their website.

386
00:25:18,364 --> 00:25:21,466
Or maybe you find the recruiter on LinkedIn. Just ask them.

387
00:25:23,327 --> 00:25:26,248
Now, after talking about your first approach

388
00:25:27,029 --> 00:25:31,471
and content of your application, I want to stress a very important detail

389
00:25:31,571 --> 00:25:36,814
about the general appearance, which is, please help me understand you.

390
00:25:37,884 --> 00:25:40,385
I might just drop your application if I cannot read it.

391
00:25:40,945 --> 00:25:43,887
And with that, I mean, please don't send in your CV

392
00:25:44,087 --> 00:25:46,729
or application in your mother tongue

393
00:25:48,070 --> 00:25:50,711
if the company is not using that language as a company

394
00:25:50,751 --> 00:25:51,532
language anyway.

395
00:25:52,472 --> 00:25:54,193
Keep in mind that your recruiter might not

396
00:25:54,294 --> 00:25:55,314
understand this language.

397
00:25:56,795 --> 00:26:01,438
So also keep in mind image resolutions.

398
00:26:01,978 --> 00:26:05,400
If you send in your portfolio and your CV.

399
00:26:06,987 --> 00:26:09,929
Make it a PDF. This is always the best thing that you can do.

400
00:26:11,890 --> 00:26:14,391
Try checking your grammar. Very important thing.

401
00:26:14,411 --> 00:26:18,994
A simple spellcheck tool can improve your application immensely.

402
00:26:19,014 --> 00:26:22,516
And these are just the basics of a good application.

403
00:26:22,536 --> 00:26:27,638
But how do you deal with possible rejection afterwards?

404
00:26:29,301 --> 00:26:35,242
First of all, always remember rejecting you rarely has anything to do with your talent

405
00:26:35,623 --> 00:26:42,664
and of course not your person. Except if you send me emojis like the ones you see up there.

406
00:26:43,464 --> 00:26:47,225
Please don't put yourself on a blacklist because word goes around in the industry.

407
00:26:47,245 --> 00:26:53,707
Usually we're looking for something very specific and between lots and lots of applicants

408
00:26:54,067 --> 00:26:57,468
it's very hard to make a decision but it has to be made.

409
00:26:58,840 --> 00:27:06,586
And if you reply, stay friendly, maybe ask for feedback, put yourself out there, apply again.

410
00:27:08,847 --> 00:27:17,794
So now that you know what not to do, here's a short checklist of things to consider before you send out your application.

411
00:27:19,536 --> 00:27:26,261
First of all, what do I apply for? Which position and company are you applying for? Make sure to mention it.

412
00:27:27,804 --> 00:27:34,049
Does the position fit me? And this is always a two-sided thing. Not only does it fit you,

413
00:27:34,890 --> 00:27:37,832
do you fit in? Please consider both.

414
00:27:40,234 --> 00:27:45,138
Whom am I addressing? So either you know who your recruiter or HR person is,

415
00:27:45,779 --> 00:27:51,684
maybe even check LinkedIn, or just keep it completely neutral. You'll be on the safe side.

416
00:27:53,865 --> 00:27:59,350
What do they want to see? And here we are back again at read the job posting. Usually you can

417
00:27:59,430 --> 00:28:06,736
find all required documents in there. A CV, portfolio, references, maybe salary expectation

418
00:28:06,856 --> 00:28:12,601
or the earliest starting date. And those are just some of the possible required informations

419
00:28:12,641 --> 00:28:20,608
that we will ask for. Make sure to hand those in completely. And most of all, don't give up.

420
00:28:22,387 --> 00:28:27,369
Thank you for listening. I hope these tips help you to start your journey into the game industry.

421
00:28:28,369 --> 00:28:34,671
And if you have questions, please throw them in the chat or contact me on Discord or LinkedIn.

