00:30:15,389 --> 00:30:21,693
because he already made D&D campaigns and a lot of other games and I thought I wasn't as good as him

442
00:30:21,713 --> 00:30:28,517
and my parents weren't that supportive at that time, so I didn't start at that time with studying

443
00:30:28,857 --> 00:30:30,438
instead I studied Chinese.

444
00:30:30,978 --> 00:30:35,861
But in my second year of Chinese, I just realized I really wanted to study game design.

445
00:30:36,161 --> 00:30:43,065
So I went to the Open Day, which was in December, which was a very bad, well, it was quite a bad day

446
00:30:43,145 --> 00:30:46,486
because, well, the trains were late and the venue was almost closed.

447
00:30:47,047 --> 00:30:52,749
but I still went in the building and I just by mere surprise saw Brian sitting there.

448
00:30:52,769 --> 00:30:58,372
He was also very surprised and I told him that I was thinking about studying game design

449
00:30:59,012 --> 00:31:03,634
and he told me that he believed that if I just lock myself up and just made a portfolio

450
00:31:03,994 --> 00:31:05,335
I would be able to get in.

451
00:31:06,240 --> 00:31:09,422
And as he told so, he was right.

452
00:31:09,702 --> 00:31:12,744
I got in and I studied game design.

453
00:31:13,345 --> 00:31:16,567
I'm so glad that at that time I saw Brian there,

454
00:31:16,967 --> 00:31:21,250
because most likely I needed a little push to just go for it,

455
00:31:21,370 --> 00:31:23,212
to have those little extra guts.

456
00:31:23,672 --> 00:31:26,254
So thanks to Brian, I studied game design.

457
00:31:29,433 --> 00:31:33,214
Okay, so I was studying game design and Chinese at the same time,

458
00:31:33,614 --> 00:31:38,495
so I wanted to combine both studies by doing an internship in Taiwan.

459
00:31:38,515 --> 00:31:43,156
I went to the student coordinator and she, well, she shaked her head.

460
00:31:43,236 --> 00:31:47,537
She said, no, you should go to Japan. I was quite confused because

461
00:31:48,217 --> 00:31:54,119
they're total different countries. And, well, she told me if I really wanted to

462
00:31:54,159 --> 00:31:55,579
go, I should just...

463
00:31:56,593 --> 00:32:02,055
do it by myself. So I just applied, I mean I basically write my own emails to

464
00:32:02,155 --> 00:32:07,397
companies in Taiwan and none of them replied me back. So the deadline of the

465
00:32:07,457 --> 00:32:12,819
internship was getting close. So I just thought maybe I should just call them. So

466
00:32:12,879 --> 00:32:17,661
I basically called all the companies in Taiwan that I could find. I was just like

467
00:32:17,741 --> 00:32:22,523
hey hello, I'm Madina, I can speak a bit of Chinese, can you give me a job?

468
00:32:23,079 --> 00:32:29,368
I felt quite stupid and basically they thought I was very cute, but most likely I wouldn't get a job out of it.

469
00:32:29,929 --> 00:32:33,954
Luckily there was a very nice lady who asked me for my email address,

470
00:32:34,555 --> 00:32:38,660
but she thought my email address was quite long, so she asked my Skype instead.

471
00:32:39,515 --> 00:32:47,738
And that was like the golden ticket because as he gave her Skype, I could contact her back.

472
00:32:48,198 --> 00:32:52,299
And I basically got a job at her company, which is great.

473
00:32:52,780 --> 00:32:57,881
I think in this story, it's very interesting to know that the student coordinator wanted me to do

474
00:32:58,241 --> 00:33:00,822
something that all other people already did.

475
00:33:01,422 --> 00:33:06,743
but I just knew that I really wanted to go to Taiwan and I created the opportunity by myself.

476
00:33:07,344 --> 00:33:13,925
And I think it is really good to sometimes listen to what you really want because you know best.

477
00:33:16,026 --> 00:33:23,307
Okay, so I was just scrolling on Facebook and checking some nice pictures of cats and kittens

478
00:33:24,027 --> 00:33:30,289
and then suddenly there was a job offer which sounded very vague but it was in Hong Kong and

479
00:33:30,329 --> 00:33:31,089
I really like that.

480
00:33:32,132 --> 00:33:35,895
But it just asked for a service learning teacher.

481
00:33:35,915 --> 00:33:37,837
I had no clue what it was.

482
00:33:38,278 --> 00:33:41,701
So the first thing I did was just searching on Google

483
00:33:41,721 --> 00:33:42,662
what service learning.

484
00:33:43,103 --> 00:33:44,945
And I just find out that service learning

485
00:33:45,045 --> 00:33:48,408
is a way of teaching that not only benefits the students,

486
00:33:48,468 --> 00:33:49,890
but also the community.

487
00:33:50,530 --> 00:33:50,871
Well, that.

488
00:33:51,854 --> 00:33:57,336
made me think because like quite a lot of games have the same purpose, especially applied games.

489
00:33:57,796 --> 00:34:05,319
So I looked at all the games that I worked on during my studies and I just, we made a total

490
00:34:05,459 --> 00:34:15,643
other portfolio, like a different CV and I made a total different portfolio.

491
00:34:17,202 --> 00:34:24,390
focused on service learning and I succeeded in that because most likely they liked that I really

492
00:34:24,470 --> 00:34:30,997
focused on it and I got the job and I think it was the best job I ever had because I made

493
00:34:31,698 --> 00:34:34,561
design my own courses and teach them as well.

494
00:34:35,922 --> 00:34:43,371
So in this story, it's interesting to know that I thought that the job offer was really strange,

495
00:34:43,451 --> 00:34:46,735
but still too good to be true. Well, sometimes...

496
00:34:47,839 --> 00:34:54,843
It is too good to be true, so sometimes you should just be a little bit curious to just go for it.

497
00:34:55,463 --> 00:35:02,086
Well, that's my motto. And also, if you think that you can't find a job or opportunities in

498
00:35:02,146 --> 00:35:07,709
your home country, just believe me, it is so easy to go to the other side of the world.

499
00:35:08,269 --> 00:35:12,871
Well, not now, but later on it will be easy again. So please don't forget that.

500
00:35:13,752 --> 00:35:19,702
I hope my personal stories inspired you to just change your own mindset and just go for it.

501
00:35:20,944 --> 00:35:26,012
Next up is Jonas who's going to explain how to apply for a job. See ya!

502
00:35:26,596 --> 00:35:32,801
Hey everybody, my name is Jonas Pastors and I'm a junior game designer and junior narrative designer at Gaming Mind Studios.

503
00:35:33,122 --> 00:35:38,727
In my section of the Schmalky Talk, I'm going to go through the application process from the perspective of someone looking for a job

504
00:35:39,107 --> 00:35:45,012
and I'm going to give you general tips, tricks and insights that I learned while looking for my first full-time position myself.

505
00:35:45,733 --> 00:35:47,835
Now, to start off with a quick word about my profile.

506
00:35:48,756 --> 00:35:53,300
I was looking for a job between June and September 2020, right after I'd got my master's degree.

507
00:35:54,060 --> 00:35:58,282
At the time, I had about 10 months of experience within internships and general side hustles,

508
00:35:58,702 --> 00:36:03,025
and I consider my expertise being within NPC design, and I naturally wanted to find a job

509
00:36:03,065 --> 00:36:07,947
to reflect that. Now, to find opportunities to apply to, I mainly went through my network.

510
00:36:08,348 --> 00:36:11,989
I'd created it over the course of my studies, going to conferences, talking to people,

511
00:36:12,250 --> 00:36:16,792
connecting with them, and now I was able to regularly check Facebook, LinkedIn, Twitter,

512
00:36:17,192 --> 00:36:19,133
anywhere where they would share relevant positions.

513
00:36:21,333 --> 00:36:26,977
Another thing I did was to go through lists of companies in the general area I was looking for a job in, being Western Europe.

514
00:36:27,357 --> 00:36:31,221
And what this allowed me to do was to find plenty of companies I'd never heard of before,

515
00:36:31,961 --> 00:36:34,563
but who were still looking to fill relevant positions to me.

516
00:36:35,104 --> 00:36:37,786
Fun fact, I ended up finding my job via this method.

517
00:36:38,727 --> 00:36:41,048
A great resource I can recommend is GameDevMap,

518
00:36:41,669 --> 00:36:47,454
which is a great repository of information about companies, their locations, and generally what they do,

519
00:36:47,854 --> 00:36:50,196
which is really great if you're looking for something specific.

520
00:36:51,201 --> 00:36:54,723
A third way to generate opportunities for me was to get my profile out there.

521
00:36:55,543 --> 00:36:59,306
If you've been studying for a while and if you've been preparing to go into the industry,

522
00:36:59,586 --> 00:37:02,408
it's likely that you have one or two cool projects under your belt.

523
00:37:02,548 --> 00:37:06,871
What I can recommend is to get them out there, put them on sites like itch.io, present them

524
00:37:06,931 --> 00:37:11,474
on your portfolio, anything to get your profile out there and maybe get discovered by a recruiter.

525
00:37:12,475 --> 00:37:18,176
The way I went about this was to write a Gamasutra article based on the research I did for my master's thesis.

526
00:37:18,536 --> 00:37:25,618
The article ended up getting featured and what happened was that two companies approached me to inquire whether I would be a good fit for them.

527
00:37:27,218 --> 00:37:34,900
And even though there was only two opportunities of the 30 applications I wrote, I still consider them to be the most valuable because they approached me.

528
00:37:35,060 --> 00:37:37,840
I didn't have to convince them that I knew what I was talking about.

529
00:37:38,863 --> 00:37:42,925
Still, I ended up writing about 30, 31 applications.

530
00:37:43,365 --> 00:37:49,149
And what you will find after the first couple, that there's a lot of information to keep

531
00:37:49,189 --> 00:37:49,549
track of.

532
00:37:49,889 --> 00:37:53,451
So what I found, it is really important to keep organized.

533
00:37:53,851 --> 00:37:58,534
And I did that in a way by keeping this handy little table with the company name, with the

534
00:37:58,574 --> 00:38:04,197
position, with a link to the position so I could check back later, and the general status

535
00:38:04,317 --> 00:38:05,078
of the application.

536
00:38:07,306 --> 00:38:11,848
And what was especially valuable I found was this last contact column on the right,

537
00:38:11,908 --> 00:38:14,790
because sometimes companies will take a little while to respond to you.

538
00:38:15,110 --> 00:38:21,453
And it's always good to know when they wrote last, so you know whether you can inquire without being too pushy.

539
00:38:22,273 --> 00:38:27,016
What you might also notice is that I applied to a wide range of different positions.

540
00:38:27,496 --> 00:38:30,697
World designer, UX designer, game designer, narrative designer.

541
00:38:31,418 --> 00:38:35,200
And I had to do that because there were very few positions.

542
00:38:35,919 --> 00:38:42,222
that seemed tailor-made for what I could do, so I had to be flexible. Flexible in what I was looking

543
00:38:42,262 --> 00:38:48,486
for, flexible in what I wanted to do, and I was able to do this because during my studies and

544
00:38:48,566 --> 00:38:57,011
generally when looking at games, I didn't just stick to the field I wanted to work in. When I

545
00:38:57,352 --> 00:39:03,215
wanted to do my internship, I wanted to do narrative. The company that I ended up working with

546
00:39:03,934 --> 00:39:10,757
needed game design, so I did game design for them. And now when I was looking for a full-time position,

547
00:39:10,857 --> 00:39:15,399
I wanted to do game design. The company I am with now asked me if I can do narrative,

548
00:39:15,699 --> 00:39:23,382
and I said, yeah, sure. So while you're studying, keep your eyes open for different things adjacent

549
00:39:23,402 --> 00:39:28,244
to what you are interested in and what you're doing right now. Be curious. You might never know

550
00:39:28,724 --> 00:39:32,565
what skill set you acquire at the site will get you a job in the end.

551
00:39:33,418 --> 00:39:39,141
Now, if you've written enough applications, eventually you will be doing an interview.

552
00:39:40,622 --> 00:39:47,365
And what I found worked really good for me was to be engaging, smile a lot, consider it a

553
00:39:48,206 --> 00:39:52,788
nice conversation with a partner, not with someone who has your life in their hands.

554
00:39:53,468 --> 00:39:58,591
You've written enough applications, you will get other interviews with other companies.

555
00:39:58,631 --> 00:39:59,531
So don't stress about it.

556
00:40:00,324 --> 00:40:04,047
Be pleasant to talk to and this already goes a long way.

557
00:40:05,348 --> 00:40:07,029
However, be prepared for tough questions.

558
00:40:08,450 --> 00:40:10,211
Beforehand, consider your own profile,

559
00:40:10,231 --> 00:40:13,934
try to make out weaknesses and try

560
00:40:13,954 --> 00:40:16,275
to come up with answers for tough questions.

561
00:40:16,556 --> 00:40:18,337
Say, if there's a gap in your CV,

562
00:40:19,218 --> 00:40:20,679
think about what you might answer.

563
00:40:21,179 --> 00:40:23,501
What's also important is that you have your own questions

564
00:40:23,561 --> 00:40:23,901
prepared.

565
00:40:25,313 --> 00:40:26,093
Ideally, you have a list.

566
00:40:26,113 --> 00:40:31,597
You don't need to ask all of them, but what that shows is that you have taken the time

567
00:40:31,637 --> 00:40:36,480
to prepare for the interview and that you have taken the time to take an interest in

568
00:40:36,520 --> 00:40:38,981
the company, and this also goes a long way.

569
00:40:39,622 --> 00:40:45,745
Now, what usually followed an interview for me was a design test, and they were usually

570
00:40:45,785 --> 00:40:47,627
between two and 10 days in duration.

571
00:40:47,767 --> 00:40:52,429
What you see on the right is a two-day design test where I had to create some logic in Unreal

572
00:40:52,490 --> 00:40:52,710
Engine.

573
00:40:53,537 --> 00:40:57,918
And what's really important here is that you take the necessary time to complete them,

574
00:40:58,319 --> 00:41:05,821
because the companies are looking for how you do with limited time and limited instructions.

575
00:41:07,001 --> 00:41:11,402
And what's totally cool to do is to ask to postpone it if you don't have the time to

576
00:41:12,462 --> 00:41:16,844
do that right now. The design test on the right I got on a workday, it was during a conference,

577
00:41:17,024 --> 00:41:20,225
I did not have the time to complete it. So I asked them.

578
00:41:20,973 --> 00:41:22,834
hey, is it cool if I do it during the weekend?

579
00:41:22,874 --> 00:41:24,215
They were like, sure, why not?

580
00:41:24,375 --> 00:41:25,956
They hadn't given me the information

581
00:41:28,058 --> 00:41:30,380
that I needed to complete it, so that was totally cool.

582
00:41:31,100 --> 00:41:33,722
I did the design test, and I ended up getting an offer.

583
00:41:34,923 --> 00:41:38,225
So definitely take the time, and if it's not a good time for you,

584
00:41:38,986 --> 00:41:39,726
try to postpone it.

585
00:41:40,747 --> 00:41:43,769
Now, ideally, after a design test, you will get an offer.

586
00:41:44,109 --> 00:41:44,750
You may take it.

587
00:41:44,790 --> 00:41:46,191
You may keep searching.

588
00:41:46,991 --> 00:41:49,613
But ideally, you will have a job at the end.

589
00:41:50,250 --> 00:41:55,753
I hope these tips are useful to you and I hope to see you in the Q&A section.

590
00:41:56,654 --> 00:41:59,976
Hi, I'm Klaus. I've worked as a storyboard artist on games like Hitman,

591
00:42:00,156 --> 00:42:05,200
Risen of Rome and Horizon Forbidden West. In this presentation, I want to talk with you about

592
00:42:05,520 --> 00:42:10,923
creating opportunities. I have six tips for you that are especially important if you're starting

593
00:42:10,963 --> 00:42:17,148
your job hunt but you don't have a network yet. And then I have this one anecdote from my own

594
00:42:17,228 --> 00:42:19,209
career where I did everything wrong.

595
00:42:19,934 --> 00:42:24,617
But before we dive into that, a quick word on opportunities in general.

596
00:42:25,298 --> 00:42:30,301
They are everywhere, even beyond all these well-known international conferences

597
00:42:30,341 --> 00:42:31,122
we like to attend.

598
00:42:31,142 --> 00:42:35,605
It could be a career day at your university with a panel discussion on stage.

599
00:42:35,685 --> 00:42:39,507
It could be a social event that is industry related, like a life drawing class

600
00:42:40,228 --> 00:42:42,750
or a workshop where industry professionals are present.

601
00:42:43,450 --> 00:42:45,011
All these can improve your reach.

602
00:42:45,712 --> 00:42:46,192
Secondly.

603
00:42:46,968 --> 00:42:50,490
Remember, 100% of all jobs are given to you by humans.

604
00:42:51,290 --> 00:42:53,931
Therefore, the more relevant people you know, the better.

605
00:42:54,872 --> 00:42:58,853
Now, for some people, meeting others means a lot of stress, and we don't need that.

606
00:42:59,454 --> 00:43:00,794
This brings me to my first tip.

607
00:43:01,835 --> 00:43:03,355
Think it's not going to happen today.

608
00:43:04,336 --> 00:43:07,758
Odds are, you will not sign a contract right there at the conference,

609
00:43:08,238 --> 00:43:11,879
especially not at your very first portfolio review ever.

610
00:43:12,560 --> 00:43:13,680
Therefore, relax.

611
00:43:14,974 --> 00:43:18,717
The worst thing that can happen to you is that you get no job and you don't have a good time.

612
00:43:19,157 --> 00:43:20,858
So please try to enjoy yourself.

613
00:43:21,579 --> 00:43:26,182
You will be more approachable this way too for others who also seek those new connections.

614
00:43:26,743 --> 00:43:29,385
Really, we are all there to network after all.

615
00:43:30,185 --> 00:43:31,586
So what do I want to aim for?

616
00:43:32,047 --> 00:43:32,407
My tip?

617
00:43:33,182 --> 00:43:34,163
Go for the silver medal.

618
00:43:35,043 --> 00:43:36,944
Imagine the decision is already made,

619
00:43:37,524 --> 00:43:39,966
because unless you're a genius newcomer,

620
00:43:40,266 --> 00:43:44,108
you will not get the first most awesome open position or gig.

621
00:43:44,828 --> 00:43:47,829
Instead, aim at the second job the producer or editor

622
00:43:47,869 --> 00:43:48,450
needs to fill.

623
00:43:49,050 --> 00:43:50,891
But Klaus, how do I get in line for that?

624
00:43:51,451 --> 00:43:53,512
By building a network of peers.

625
00:43:54,272 --> 00:43:57,114
So seek business partners, not clients.

626
00:43:58,039 --> 00:44:00,962
Your peers and colleagues are the most important part of your network.

627
00:44:01,382 --> 00:44:03,424
It's not only about potential clients.

628
00:44:04,364 --> 00:44:06,966
Use any opportunity to connect with your peers.

629
00:44:07,147 --> 00:44:09,709
For example, while waiting in line for that job interview.

630
00:44:10,429 --> 00:44:13,192
Ask them how they got into the industry and look at their portfolios.

631
00:44:13,952 --> 00:44:17,715
If the vibe is right, see if you can get a group together for dinner.

632
00:44:18,256 --> 00:44:21,358
It might even be fun because in the end we're all nerds, right?

633
00:44:22,639 --> 00:44:23,840
They are not your competition.

634
00:44:25,443 --> 00:44:28,264
And these people can become your friends or allies.

635
00:44:28,924 --> 00:44:30,565
Companies give away jobs.

636
00:44:31,045 --> 00:44:32,385
Nobody can steal them from you.

637
00:44:33,146 --> 00:44:35,927
If they get the job you wanted, they were just a better fit.

638
00:44:36,687 --> 00:44:40,188
And you all of a sudden have a colleague or friend at your dream company.

639
00:44:40,848 --> 00:44:43,629
So when the time comes that this company has more jobs to give away,

640
00:44:44,209 --> 00:44:45,310
who do you think gets the call?

641
00:44:45,870 --> 00:44:47,050
They call the silver medal guy.

642
00:44:48,131 --> 00:44:52,072
This is how I got my first geek drawing Transformers comics for IDW back in the day.

643
00:44:52,913 --> 00:44:53,433
True story.

644
00:44:55,029 --> 00:44:57,772
Point number four, be a force for good at the conference.

645
00:44:57,992 --> 00:44:59,013
Be present.

646
00:44:59,654 --> 00:45:00,755
Interact at a panel.

647
00:45:01,015 --> 00:45:05,199
Sit first row, take notes, make eye contact, ask a question.

648
00:45:06,214 --> 00:45:08,556
Always good, help somebody that is under stress,

649
00:45:08,996 --> 00:45:10,638
which is a common thing at a conference.

650
00:45:11,118 --> 00:45:11,798
Hold the door.

651
00:45:12,079 --> 00:45:13,980
If they look lost, help them to their meeting room.

652
00:45:14,541 --> 00:45:16,462
Lend somebody a pen or an aspirin.

653
00:45:17,122 --> 00:45:17,723
Be giving.

654
00:45:18,403 --> 00:45:19,484
Just don't be obtrusive

655
00:45:19,945 --> 00:45:21,726
and don't expect anything back right there.

656
00:45:22,266 --> 00:45:24,128
This way, the second time you bump into each other,

657
00:45:24,368 --> 00:45:26,490
maybe a year later at the next conference,

658
00:45:27,130 --> 00:45:28,571
they will remember you fondly

659
00:45:29,072 --> 00:45:30,473
and that's where things get moving.

660
00:45:31,093 --> 00:45:32,234
So when you made it this far,

661
00:45:32,434 --> 00:45:34,276
especially with potential clients,

662
00:45:35,388 --> 00:45:36,368
Get their business card.

663
00:45:37,029 --> 00:45:38,749
Again, get their business card.

664
00:45:39,410 --> 00:45:41,951
Don't worry about getting your card into their hands.

665
00:45:42,491 --> 00:45:45,313
Assume that you will need to be able to reach them,

666
00:45:45,333 --> 00:45:46,653
not vice versa.

667
00:45:47,274 --> 00:45:49,955
Bonus tip, scribble notes directly on their card

668
00:45:50,095 --> 00:45:50,675
after the meeting.

669
00:45:51,075 --> 00:45:53,837
Stuff like location, occasion, talking points,

670
00:45:53,917 --> 00:45:57,078
because when you contact them after the conference,

671
00:45:57,599 --> 00:45:59,500
you want to remind them how they know you.

672
00:46:00,409 --> 00:46:04,353
Anything can be important if you want to recreate the moment you met them in their minds.

673
00:46:04,854 --> 00:46:06,916
And that brings me to my most important point today.

674
00:46:08,357 --> 00:46:13,863
Everybody counts. I know everybody wants to get a minute with a big CEO or this superstar artist

675
00:46:14,003 --> 00:46:19,508
after the panel on stage. Please look beyond that one opportunity. Talk with other people

676
00:46:19,568 --> 00:46:23,292
in the line. They could be your future colleagues who might refer jobs to you.

677
00:46:24,010 --> 00:46:28,932
talk with the VIP's friend or spouse right next to them or their personal assistant

678
00:46:30,012 --> 00:46:36,195
or volunteer convention organizer because first it's just totally impolite to ignore them and

679
00:46:36,275 --> 00:46:40,597
second they might have more industry insights and connections than you can see at first glance.

680
00:46:41,357 --> 00:46:45,899
They will appreciate being seen and they will have a very good reason for being there just as you do.

681
00:46:46,680 --> 00:46:52,082
Literally everybody can be important. And this last advice brings me to my unfortunate

682
00:46:53,022 --> 00:46:58,626
anecdote where I did everything wrong. It was in 2001. I was in America for the first time

683
00:46:58,647 --> 00:47:04,471
and I attended San Diego Comic Con in California. I was already published in Germany and had what I

684
00:47:04,551 --> 00:47:10,475
thought was a high standard for comics. I wasn't into serious action comics, realistically drawn

685
00:47:10,515 --> 00:47:16,140
with high-end computer coloring. So I was walking by a not very exciting looking booth which was

686
00:47:16,220 --> 00:47:22,204
manned by someone who looked like your typical tall beardy comic book guy. Pretty unassuming.

687
00:47:23,097 --> 00:47:26,298
and he tried to sell me his comic. It was called Battle Pope.

688
00:47:27,278 --> 00:47:32,221
It was in black and white, tongue in cheek and definitely not high-end superheroes.

689
00:47:32,941 --> 00:47:34,301
I wasn't impressed by the book.

690
00:47:35,002 --> 00:47:37,863
I dismissed the publishing effort and him, the guy who wrote the book,

691
00:47:38,423 --> 00:47:40,944
and I indeed didn't ask for his business card.

692
00:47:41,865 --> 00:47:44,526
I still bought an issue of his books out of courtesy

693
00:47:45,066 --> 00:47:48,427
and found it surprisingly entertaining when I read it on the flight back to Germany.

694
00:47:48,447 --> 00:47:50,368
I never saw the guy again.

695
00:47:51,744 --> 00:47:57,367
Later on, it turns out, he did another black and white independent comic, which was a bit of a success.

696
00:47:57,948 --> 00:48:00,890
It was called The Walking Dead. You might have heard about it.

697
00:48:01,450 --> 00:48:05,712
And then he also did a superhero comic, even in color, it's called Invincible,

698
00:48:05,752 --> 00:48:08,814
which is now streaming as an animated series on Amazon Prime.

699
00:48:10,335 --> 00:48:13,957
Yes, I completely ignored the legendary writer and creator Robert Kirkman.

700
00:48:15,758 --> 00:48:17,659
So please be nice to everybody, because...

701
00:48:18,513 --> 00:48:22,256
Everybody can be an important contact in your future career network.

702
00:48:22,876 --> 00:48:25,859
With a bit of luck, I will see you at our next business opportunity.

703
00:48:26,419 --> 00:48:27,120
Thanks for listening.

